对话人类学家项飙：怎么去面对已知无解的问题http://www.infzm.com/contents/260661 <div>;<i>;2023-11-15 18:00:00</i>;</div>;<p>;Xiang Biao sat among a group of young people in Guangzhou, laughing with everyone, occasionally frowning and speaking, More often than not, listening to each person’s thoughts, experiences, and traumas. Most of these traumas come from family of origin and close relationships. Sometimes everyone forgets that Xiang Biao exists. During a party, he quietly got up to wash the dishes, and almost no one noticed him. These young people are participants in the "Seeing the First 500 Meters" social art workshop launched by artists He Zhisen and Xiang Biao, as well as Duan Zhipeng, a doctoral student at the Oslo School of Architecture and Design. The works of the workshop have participated in the 9th Shenzhen-Hong Kong Urban/Architecture Biennale. </p>; <p>;The last time Xiang Biao returned to China was in 2019 before the epidemic. Xiang Biao is the director of the Max Planck Institute for Social Anthropology in Germany and a professor of social anthropology at the University of Oxford in the UK. He became famous for his research on Zhejiang Village in Beijing. After many years abroad, he has become active in the Chinese-speaking world again in recent years. </p>; <p>;When Xiang Biao returned to China this time, he frequently chatted with various people. For example, every time he took a taxi, he didn’t want to miss the opportunity to talk to the driver. In his hometown of Wenzhou, he found that most taxi drivers were over 45 years old and usually had another job. A driver told Xiang Biao that he helped people open credit cards. Xiang Biao was curious about who else was using credit cards now that mobile payment is so convenient. The driver said that some people need small loans for short-term turnover. And looking for customers to open a card involves the gray chain of data buying and selling. In an online car-hailing car in Guangzhou, when the conversation came up about the career of the driver's son, he pointed to the platform recording equipment in the car and made a shushing gesture, and the conversation stopped. "These are all new points for me. I don't know if they are useful, but they can help me discover the richness of society." Xiang Biao told Southern Weekend reporters. </p>; <p>;Xiang Biao said that he is a person who is far away from art. He almost never watches movies and rarely goes to art galleries and exhibition halls. There was only one exception when he served as a judge for a German artist’s application project. . "This is a German habit, to find people with different subject backgrounds to participate in the review." He said. The "Seeing the First 500 Meters" workshop is his most in-depth participation in a public art and social art activity. His original idea was to encourage everyone to go to the community and meet strangers, but on the one hand, due to the uncertainty caused by the epidemic in 2022; on the other hand, many people found that if the radius of 500 meters continued to be reduced, the things they were most concerned about would be , is family and companionship. As a result, many of the workshop's works were skewed. Everyone's anxiety is superimposed on social and personal life. </p>; <p>;He Zhisen once held an exhibition in a vegetable market in Guangzhou. On the podium of South China University of Technology, he said that he had held more than 100 workshops, and most of them dispersed after seeing the first 500 people. m” members are the most closely connected. I heard that Xiang Biao made a special trip to Guangzhou to chat with everyone. Some of the participants in the workshop came from Nanjing and some from abroad. On this day, Xiang Biao sat quietly in the back row of the lecture hall, like an older student. He followed workshop member Manman through the noisy lanes and handshake buildings of Shipai Village to the art space in the urban village. This space, known as the "mobile club", was originally a garbage recycling station. Xiang Biao talked with everyone about Wenzhou, the south, and the differences between the north and the south of China. </p>; <p>;<img src="http://images.infzm.com/cms/medias/image/23/11/15/pV6FUnCDyc5oDAwewe9FJCGkWMNjCZKxZczL7bL2.jpg" border="0" width="960" height= "720" data-src="//images.infzm.com/cms/medias/image/23/11/15/pV6FUnCDyc5oDAwewe9FJCGkWMNjCZKxZczL7bL2.jpg" data-key="258366">;</p>; <p style="color : #999; text-align: center;">;In October 2023, Xiang Biao (first from left in the back row) communicated with young people at the "Mobile Club", an art space in Guangzhou. <span style="color: #aaa;">;</span>;</p>; <p>;Xiang Biao found that he was more popular among young people in China than he imagined, but he did not feel that he was a young person not as a mentor but as an interlocutor. Dialogue research is also his working method in facing the research direction of "common anxiety". In October 2023, Southern Weekend reporters conducted an exclusive interview with Xiang Biao in Guangzhou. </p>; <h4>;Understanding art through anthropology, "recognition" is different from "understanding"</h4>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: Kaiti, Kaiti_GB2312, STKaiti;">;Why has the contemporary art world paid more and more attention to anthropology in recent years? </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Xiang Biao: </strong>;<span>;The so-called elite art collected in galleries and museums can do a lot in terms of methods, techniques and forms of expression. But if it is public art, if you only make breakthroughs in form and method, it will be meaningless to the common people. Others will not know what your breakthrough is, and it cannot evoke that kind of resonance. The common people will not understand what you are doing. If there is no connection with his life, then he cannot participate or be further stimulated. </span>;</p>; <p>;At this time, public art needs to be ideological, to find a problem, and then this problem can be expressed in a very condensed artistic way, whether it is a drama, an installation, or a painting. Well, once you express it, everyone can recognize it, and at the same time, the way you express it makes everyone see that this is a door, and they can't help but open it. There is a space behind the door. This way everyone can participate. </p>; <p>;Such an artistic work must have a certain degree of thought, a large amount of observation of experience, a very detailed and sincere appreciation, and then sublimate an image, a motif, and a core symbol. </p>; <p>;Then why is anthropology, rather than general social sciences or psychology, communicating with art? Because anthropology is to see some problems and truths from very specific experiences. It is not like philosophy, which starts from an existing problem, such as "What is a good person?"; it is also not like sociology, Think about it from a macro social phenomenon. Anthropology uses daily behavior to see some of the problems behind it, so anthropology has a strong sense of recognition. People can tell at a glance that this is related to them. </p>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: KaiTi, KaiTi_GB2312, STKaiti;">;How do you understand "sense of recognition"? </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Xiang Biao: </strong>;<span>;Recognition means that when you see something, it evokes your understanding of your own life experience, and it will produce a mutual projection. So recognition is very important. Our understanding of the world must be based on our own life experience. You mobilize your memory and then make a new interpretation of this thing. This is called recognition. If you don’t understand, you just don’t recognize it. </span>;</p>; <p>;For example, whether it is Kafka or Benjamin, if we do not have a good understanding of European culture, we cannot recognize them. In fact, what he said is very direct in his context, and it is easy for people with similar life experiences to recognize it. </p>; <p>;Just like when we look at Lu Xun, it is difficult for young people today to understand Lu Xun, also because they do not recognize it. This does not mean that you can solve it through knowledge and logic. Of course, it does not rule out that there is a purely literal and logical way. You think you understand it, but you are completely unable to mobilize your own experience. (This situation) actually happens a lot. We all feel this way when we read some documents. </p>; <p>;There are many people who engage in academic research and art. In fact, their understanding is not based on their own life experience, but on establishing relationships between texts, which can also form an understanding. Or logical interpretation, it feels like you understand it, but the effect of this understanding is very different from what we call "recognition". </p>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: KaiTi, KaiTi_GB2312, STKaiti;">;The participants of the workshop you met in Guangzhou this time, Most of them are very young. Did you encounter any new excitement while communicating with everyone? </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Xiang Biao: </strong>;<span>;Of course there is a lot of excitement. They are not willing to adopt the mainstream meritocracy (to live), and may not necessarily be successful in a secular sense. Some people have just resigned. Their backgrounds are quite diverse, including carpenters, civil servants, video makers, and marketers. There are also people who study art, not particularly many, but these people all have a certain sense of art. Artistic sense means that they are more sensitive to their own perceptions. They may not necessarily think about these sensitivities, but the "sensitivity" will stay on him or her, and it is a bit sticky and will not be easily brushed off. Artistic people are sensitive and adhesive people. </span>;</p>; <p>;The workshop was a great education for me. It made me softer and paid more attention to people's subjective emotions. As I just said, these young people are not very mainstream. Many of them are weak and not very confident. There were several people who could barely speak at the beginning of last year, couldn't sleep the day before the meeting, and were so nervous. Many young people I have interacted with before, such as students at Oxford, are very talkative. Oxford is a famous place for cultivating politicians. But many of the expressions of the young people in this workshop were inconsistent. This kind of difficult expression sometimes turns into awkward silence, but once he or she speaks, you can feel that there are very rich feelings behind it. </p>; <p>;According to my previous habits, the efficiency of this kind of communication is very low. I am a relatively rational person and have been pursuing clarity. I now realize that I was actually very closed-minded and had a very single perception of the world. I need more patience, this is an education for me. I think that to promote many things here, we cannot all do them in a rational way. Art is a good tool. I listen more. Before, I didn’t pay enough attention to the richness and sensitivity of emotions, and the many mixed and unclear things, but now I pay more attention to them. </p>; <h4>;“I am not a mentor, but an interlocutor”</h4>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: 楷体, 凯体_GB2312 , STKaiti;">;How do you interact with the audience during lectures or online live broadcasts? </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Xiang Biao: </strong>;<span>;After the speech, the questions asked by the public fell into two categories. The first type is to ask questions based on the concepts I proposed. To be honest, this kind of question is not particularly meaningful. In the end, it turned into me having to define and explain the concepts. What is really impactful are the second type of questions, which are very specific questions based on life experience. It's a difficult question to answer, but it gives me some punch. For example, some parents will ask me, saying that involution is not good. My child's grades are getting worse and worse. Should I send him to tutoring? No matter how I answer, this parent will most likely send their children to make up classes. Then my answer may be, how you define make-up lessons when you interact with your children is very critical. I can feel the parent's anxiety and entanglement. I can't change the objective environment, but the more useful and appropriate answer to him is how to define, state, and treat this matter. </span>;</p>; <p>;We may need to distinguish between thinking and thoughts. Thinking is inferential and requires rigorous logic; thinking is divergent and multi-dimensional. This kind of dialogue allowed me to change from one-dimensional thinking to richer and more sensitive thinking. </p>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: KaiTi, KaiTi_GB2312, STKaiti;">;What are the differences between the academic workshops you participated in? </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Xiang Biao: </strong>;<span>;That kind of workshop requires using very clear words to express, theoretically and conceptually speaking about life, and it takes a lot of time. Generally no more than three days. This "Seeing the First 500 Meters" is completely different. It is open, does not have a fixed theme, and is against conceptualization. </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: 楷体, 凯体_GB2312, STKaiti;">;Many young people like to communicate with you, and they are very Trust you. Do you consider yourself a mentor to young people? </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Xiang Biao: </strong>;<span>;I was quite surprised when I returned to China this time. I found that I am more popular than I thought. How eager young people are. Beyond my imagination. But I don’t feel like a mentor to young people. I hate the role of mentor. When I was a young man, I didn’t pay much attention to life mentors, so I won’t become the character I hate. I am a conversationalist. </span>;</p>; <p>;I think the most important thing is not that I tell you what you should do, but that I inspire you to think more. I will raise some questions, highlight some paradoxes, do some analysis, make you think, and let us find that the original thinking may be a bit simple. This is my job. Even if I have some so-called advice, it's about how to think, not about what to do morally and behaviorally. </p>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: 楷体, 凯体_GB2312, STKaiti;">;But it is true that when many young people ask you questions, they will ask about Regarding issues such as anxiety and involution, there is a feeling of expecting you to be a life mentor. </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Xiang Biao: </strong>;<span>;I don’t think so. They would also ask each other these questions at friends' gatherings. They would say that the involution has become like this, what should I do? These questions are not only asked among friends and relatives, but also asked by oneself at night when I can't sleep. I think maybe that question occupied his mind and it would come out naturally, so he would ask that question to everyone. </span>;</p>; <p>;What’s interesting is how I answer such a question. He knew I wouldn't give him an answer, couldn't show him a path. Most people don't think so. What he actually asked was how to face a problem that is known to have no solution. So I put myself in his situation, understand his situation, and respond with sincerity, which may be more effective. This is completely a friendship-like communication, not a mentor-mentee relationship. </p>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: 楷体, 凯体_GB2312, STKaiti;">;The book "Use Yourself as a Method" is a best-seller, maybe That’s why young people are inspired by you. As an anthropologist, why have you been more willing to give interviews or appear in mass media in recent years? </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Xiang Biao: </strong>;<span>;In the 19th and 20th centuries, when social science first emerged, the world was very different from today. The difference between scholars and non-scholars at that time Very big at the time. For example, a European scholar needs to learn ancient Greek, Latin, and various philosophies. Chinese scholars like Liang Qichao and Yan Fu first introduced social sciences, and most of the people are illiterate. But in the 21st century, our youth’s level of education, their ability to think and master knowledge, and their information are no different from those of scholars. And we often think that the experts are among the people. Some of the things on site B are actually more interesting than those written by scholars in many academies. This means that academic research cannot start from its own academic propositions like it did in the 19th and 20th centuries, and write an article for two to three hundred people to read it. The public will not know what is going on. That will not work. </span>;</p>; <p>;So my work in Germany is to advocate a new research style, which does not start from academic propositions, but from public anxiety itself, using "anxiety" as the title, Come and study together. In other words, it is conversational research. Everyone has their own life and their own struggles, and the taste inside is different from what we see outside. Our output should be about how to deal with the world, giving thinking methods, concepts and theoretical perspectives, and triggering more discussions. For conversational research, communication in the public media is very important. This is my working method, not a supplementary one, but a fundamental working method. It’s not that I have any conclusions to tell you, but that they collide and deepen in the constant back and forth. </p>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: 楷体, 凯体_GB2312, STKaiti;">;What forms of communication have you received during this kind of dialogue and back-and-forth? feedback? After all, you haven’t opened an account at station B, so feedback is not given through barrage. </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Xiang Biao: </strong>;<span>;I find that contemporary art is particularly sensitive. In 2020, there will be four domestic exhibitions with the title "Nearby". In fact, "nearby" is a very vague thing in academic terms. I didn't find it very interesting myself, I just mentioned it in a general way. The “nearby” concept received enthusiastic feedback. When I proposed the term “country squire,” the feedback I received was less enthusiastic and more questioning and critical. There are also some topics that I find interesting but receive a mediocre response from the public. </span>;</p>; <p>;Someone will find my email online and write to me. It's not that the question he raised is meaningful in itself, but I will think about why he raised such a question. I know that some issues are universal, and I will have to observe them over a period of time. So feedback is not given directly to me, it requires a process. </p>; <h4>;Common Anxiety and Type 16 Personality</h4>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: 凯体, 凯体_GB2312, STKaiti;">; During your return to China, you chatted intensively with various people almost every day. Have you always been so talkative? </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Xiang Biao: </strong>;<span>;I haven’t tested it yet. I am not a very extroverted person. Sometimes I am a little socially anxious, and I have been insensitive to people's subjective emotions for a long time. I have always felt that I have mild autism. I read the biography of an analytical philosopher in Oxford. He often talked to others, but everyone found that he was indifferent to many common sense things and had no interest in interpersonal relationships. The understanding is very simple, but the analysis of some things can be very profound. I think this is very similar to me. </span>;</p>; <p>;To be honest, I am quite introverted and afraid of eating with many people. When chatting on that occasion, few people can tell the complete story of their experiences. The content of the conversation can easily turn into various fragments, gossip, and extreme stories, many of which are hearsay. I'm surprised that many intellectual elites also like to talk about this. In that environment, it was difficult for me to maintain myself. I became very quiet and wanted to end it quickly. </p>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: KaiTi, KaiTi_GB2312, STKaiti;">;Nowadays, it is very popular among Chinese young people to talk about type 16 personality. We often talk to each other Asked "Are you an I person or an E person?" What do you think of this phenomenon? </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Xiang Biao: </strong>;<span>;Personality classification is a very interesting phenomenon. It is not the same as young people’s original curiosity about psychology. If you want to understand your own mental state and understand yourself, it is now mainly a social tool. You know each other's type, and then you can profile each other, and then ask each other questions. But this question does not necessarily mean that you need to prescribe the right medicine (according to the other person's personality type). , but it means that there is no way to start communication with a natural word, and using personality classification can talk more safely. This has a lot to do with the role of social media. We are used to interacting with personas, that is, types of people and people in portraits, but we don’t quite know how to interact with the people themselves. </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: 凯体, 凯体_GB2312, STKaiti;">;Most academic research now revolves around topics , do you consider yourself a lucky person for having conversations and researching shared anxieties in this way? </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Xiang Biao: </strong>;<span>;I am very lucky. I was already very lucky in Oxford. When I arrived at the Max Planck Institute in Germany, the constraints on me became even more severe. Less, and it gives you a platform that encourages you to do weird things. In the direction of "common anxiety", we have postdocs working on "pressure" in Africa, and some working on "persistence" in Latin America. In what specific life situations, what issues and in what ways do people make persistent investments? What can this teach us. This is different from a philosophical discussion; it is a very realistic observation. </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: 楷体, 凯体_GB2312, STKaiti;">;Why do you pay special attention to "anxiety"? Why conduct conversational research starting from “shared anxieties” rather than, say, “shared concerns”? </span>;</p>; <p>;<strong>;Xiang Biao: </strong>;<span>;Public concerns are often shaped by a mainstream discourse and can be easily expressed directly with some data. Concerns are integrated and conceptual. Anxiety is emotional and closer to the experience of life itself. For ordinary people, the purpose of life is not to criticize, but to live better. Of course, there are many things worthy of criticism, but only when they come out of the purpose of their lives can criticism be implemented and facilitate their actions, and then they can change lives and people's thinking under a seemingly unchangeable structure. </span>;</p>; <p>;Studying anxiety is much more difficult than studying public concerns or a certain issue, because anxiety is a vague thing that cannot be explained clearly, let alone quantified. . This means that we must find new languages ​​and new ways of thinking. It is easy to follow the agenda, but it is also difficult to innovate. But starting from anxiety, we can better grasp the current new contradictions. </p>; <p>;<strong>;Southern Weekend:</strong>;<span style="font-family: 楷体, 凯体_GB2312, STKaiti;">;"A